{"title_page": "Peter Cullum", "text_new": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Peter Cullum\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Peter Geoffrey Cullum\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1950|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality = British\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = \n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman, philanthropist\n| title = \n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives =\n| box_width = \n}}\n'''Peter Geoffrey Cullum''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 1950) is a British businessman and philanthropist. He previously served as the executive chairman of [[Towergate Partnership]] until April 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nPeter Geoffrey Cullum was born in September 1950 in [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/KIJqRLixEyh7obc1-q5sW4XSU9s/appointments |title=Peter Geoffrey CULLUM - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House) |website=Beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?scan=1&r=201098612:5851&d=bmd_1477344112 |title=FreeBMD Entry Info |website=Freebmd.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-01-04}}</ref> In his youth, Cullum played for the Norwich City boys team and was a regular spectator at [[Carrow Road]] from the 1950s.<ref name=\"Pink\"/>\n\n==Career==\nCullum began his insurance career in 1969 with the Royal Insurance Group and progressed to sales and marketing positions within Commercial Union and ITT London and Edinburgh where he became marketing director in 1988. At the age of 21, he became the youngest person to pass the Chartered Insurance Institute fellowship examinations.<ref>{{cite web|author=Peter G. Cullum CBE, Ph.D., MBA, FCII, MCIM |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=9897116&privcapId=9859838&previousCapId=12070717&previousTitle=Paymentshield%20Limited |title=Peter G. Cullum CBE, Ph.D., MBA, FCII, MCIM: Executive Profile & Biography - Bloomberg |website=Investing.businessweek.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-04}}</ref> In 1991, Cullum joined Economic Insurance and led their return to profitability in 1993. In December 1993, he led the management buyout of Economic Insurance that was sold in 1995 to [[Hiscox]] plc. He joined Hiscox as group marketing director, a role he held until he left in 1997 to create Towergate Underwriting Group. By 2010, his personal fortune was reportedly worth \u00a31.7bn.<ref>{{cite news|author=Miles Costello |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/business/moversshakers/article4715.ece |title=Peter Cullum, of Towergate |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=2010-02-24 |accessdate=2017-01-04}}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City F.C.===\nIn 2008, Cullum offered [[Norwich City F.C.]] \u00a320m, in return for becoming the majority shareholder.<ref name=\"Pink\">{{cite news|url=http://new.pinkun.com/content/ncfc/story.aspx?brand=PINKUNOnline&category=Norwich&tBrand=PINKUNOnline&tCategory=Norwich&itemid=NOED30%20Jun%202008%2009%3A34%3A51%3A633|date=2008-06-30|title=Fans urge club to accept \u00a320m offer|publisher=The Pink 'Un|accessdate=2008-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080701174603/http://new.pinkun.com/content/ncfc/story.aspx?brand=PINKUNOnline&category=Norwich&tBrand=PinkUnOnline&tCategory=Norwich&itemid=NOED30%20Jun%202008%2009%3A34%3A51%3A633|archive-date=2008-07-01|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> In November 2008, Cullum stated his determination not to \"\"just stand by as a spectator\" if Norwich City was on the financial brink.\"<ref name=\"EDP\">[http://new.edp24.co.uk/content/Sport/story.aspx?brand=EDPOnline&category=Sport&tBrand=EDPOnline&tCategory=Sport&itemid=NOED25%20Nov%202008%2022%3A35%3A12%3A710] {{dead link|date=January 2017}}</ref> He also expressed his admiration for what [[Delia Smith]] and [[Michael Wynn-Jones]] have achieved at the club:<ref name=\"EDP\"/>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"the two of them have been brilliant for Norwich City - and I've always said that. Every home and away game they are there. They've put a lot of their own personal wealth into this. If you happen to be Abramovich and you have stuck \u00a310m into Norwich City, it's an accounting entry that barely covers the cost of a holiday. But here are two people who have put in a considerable amount of their total wealth. So I feel it's disappointing if they are now being seen by some as the devil incarnate. It's unkind and it's unfair.\"\n</blockquote>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHe has established the Cullum Family Trust Scholarships at the [[Cass Business School]] in London, which gives scholarships of \u00a310,000 to two MBA or MSc students every year.<ref>{{cite web |author=UK |url=http://www.cass.city.ac.uk/more-about-cass/support-cass/individual-giving/scholarships |title=Scholarships &#124; Cass Business School |website=Cass.city.ac.uk |date=2011-07-07 |accessdate=2017-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105090102/http://www.cass.city.ac.uk/more-about-cass/support-cass/individual-giving/scholarships |archive-date=2017-01-05 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> As a result, he was awarded an honorary doctorate of Science in Entrepreneurship by the school in 2007.\n\nHe was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 2011 New Year Honours for services to business and charity.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59647 |date=31 December 2010 |page=7 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nHe is a Conservative Party donor.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2015/apr/01/tory-100-industry-captains-party-donors-tax-avoiders</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cullum, Peter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:British business executives]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:People associated with Cass Business School]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Peter Cullum\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Peter Geoffrey Cullum\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1950|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality = British\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = \n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman, philanthropist\n| title = \n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives =\n| box_width = \n}}\n'''Peter Geoffrey Cullum''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 1950) is a British businessman and philanthropist. He previously served as the executive chairman of [[Towergate Partnership]] until April 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nPeter Geoffrey Cullum was born in September 1950 in [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/KIJqRLixEyh7obc1-q5sW4XSU9s/appointments |title=Peter Geoffrey CULLUM - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House) |website=Beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?scan=1&r=201098612:5851&d=bmd_1477344112 |title=FreeBMD Entry Info |website=Freebmd.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-01-04}}</ref> In his youth, Cullum played for the Norwich City boys team and was a regular spectator at [[Carrow Road]] from the 1950s.<ref name=\"Pink\"/>\n\n==Career==\nCullum began his insurance career in 1969 with the Royal Insurance Group and progressed to sales and mark